<lines xmlns:i18n="http://xml.zope.org/namespaces/i18n" i18n:domain="sylloge_of_codes">
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">Hello friends,</text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>3.0</delta>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>255</bRed>
        <bGreen>255</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">We have a problem.</text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>2.00</delta>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>255</bRed>
        <bGreen>255</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Our electronic communications are constantly surveilled            
        </text>
        <duration>2.00</duration>
        <delta>0.25</delta>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>255</bRed>
        <bGreen>255</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            by the NSA or the GCHQ. 
        </text>
        <duration>2.00</duration>
        <delta>0.25</delta>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>255</bRed>
        <bGreen>255</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Little seems to escape
        </text>
        <duration>2.00</duration>
        <delta>0.25</delta>
        <fRed>0</fRed>
        <fGreen>255</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>0</bRed>
        <bGreen>0</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            either the computer programs or human analysts.
        </text>
        <duration>2.00</duration>
        <delta>0.25</delta>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>0</fBlue>
        <bRed>0</bRed>
        <bGreen>255</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>
        <font>SourceSansPro-Black.otf</font>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Both pour over our data as it flows
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            under the sea
        </text>
        <fRed>0</fRed>
        <fGreen>0</fGreen>
        <fBlue>255</fBlue>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            or through the ether.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Sent in the clear,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            it's "trivial" to dig through it,
        </text>
        <fRed>255</fRed>
        <fGreen>255</fGreen>
        <fBlue>255</fBlue>
        <bRed>0</bRed>
        <bGreen>0</bGreen>
        <bBlue>255</bBlue>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            as the hackers like to say.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            So we're asked to encrypt it,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            to obfuscate it in some way.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Yet encryption is not a panacea,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            for it too can be bypassed in a plethora of ways.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            We seem to be stuck in a catch-22,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            damned if we do,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            damned if we don't.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            So we feel a lack of power,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            we feel helpless,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            we feel cynical.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            What can we do?
        </text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>3.0</delta>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            We can think more poetically.
        </text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>3.0</delta>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Computers are rather silly machines,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            only able to "understand"
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            the most basic of information.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            They can't handle the poetic
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            nor sarcasm,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            and deal pooly with hidden messages,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            pidgin,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            and nuanced meanings.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            They can't handle the unquantifiable.
        </text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>3.0</delta>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            This implies that we should create
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            more poetic forms of communication
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            that are resistant to computational analysis.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Consider this an invitation.
        </text>
        <duration>5.00</duration>
        <delta>3.0</delta>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            An invitation to create
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            a new sylloge of codes.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            A sylloge is a collection of texts.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            It's a reference to an old tradition
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            where travellers would record ancient Greek and Roman inscriptions.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Today,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            let's create a new sylloge,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            a new collection of codes that others can use.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            You might wonder what these codes could be.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Well, remember Eugenio Dittborn,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            who piggy-backed on the postal network
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            in order to transfer his artwork out of Chile.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Or remember that tale of Borges,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            where an angent kills a man with the same name as a secret location,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            in order to transmit this information to his handlers
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            through a newspaper headline.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            There's the artist Kate Rich,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            who in "Feral Trade",
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            allows anyone to request that strangers
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            bring you foodstuffs from far-off corners of the globe.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Peraps you have a sepcial way of communicating
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            with a friend or partner.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Maybe you had a secret language as a child.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Or you communicate the most amazing insights through a poem.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            All of these methods are potential ways to resist the NSA or the GCHQ.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            But we must be discreet about it.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            That's why the box in front of you exists.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            It's the sylloge itself.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            It contains a computer with a wireless network
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            that is private to this space.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            The codes will only exist within this room.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            To contribute, connect to the wireless network "sylloge_of_codes".
        </text>
        <duration>10.00</duration>
        <delta>2.0</delta>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Then go to your web browser and type in "sylloge.of.codes".
        </text>
        <duration>10.00</duration>
        <delta>2.0</delta>

    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            You'll be taken to the page where you can contribute.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            You'll be able to take one code
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            —one contributed by someone else—
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            with you when you leave.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Take it with you,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            think about it,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            pass it on,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            perhaps use it in your daily life.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            When the power of any state feels too impenetrable,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            we can fall into the depths of cynicism.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            Instead,
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            let's use our imagination to reinvent how we communicate.
        </text>
    </line>
    <line>
        <text i18n:translate="">
            And now, for a contribtion from a prior visitor to this space:
        </text>
    </line>
</lines>


